unittitle.value: Records of the Gallatin Papers Project

abstract.label: Abstract
abstract.value: The Gallatin Papers Project Began in 1958 and ended in 1970 with the publication of the microfilm edition of the Papers of Albert Gallatin. The project was initiated in 1958 and run by Bayrd Still, the chairman of the History Department, who assigned various members of the History Department to manage the project. The History Department sent the papers to the New York University Archives in 1978.

p.value:
This collection is in
                <extref ns2:href="http://www.nyu.edu/library/bobst/research/arch/gallatinpapers.htm">
                    <archref> off-site storage</archref> </extref>.

Published citations should take the following form: Identification of item, date (if known); Records Gallatin Papers Project, New York University Department of History; RG 21.3.1; box number; folder number; New York University Archives, New York University Libraries.

Professor Thomas P. Govan became Editor and Director of the project in 1965 and continued until 1967 when he left New York University for the University of Oregon. Professor Carl E. Prince, coming to the University in 1968, became the last Editor of the Gallatin Papers Project and saw the project to its completion in 1970. He also became the author of the Guide to the Microfilm Edition published at the same time. Both Thomas Govan and Carl Prince had the able assistance of Mrs. Helene H. Fineman, who came in as Associate Editor in 1966 from the Papers of Benjamin Franklin at Yale University.
There appear to be no major gaps in the collection.
